@NODE "RESTRICT" "Restricting files/dirs"
                                                               
   _________ 
    _______ )·R·e·s·t·r·i·c·t·i·n·g ·F·i·l·e·s·
           )¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯
           ¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯

If you like you can put a file called 'restrict' in the same path as this door.
In this txt file you can enter the files/dirs you don't want the user to have axx
to. You only have to write a part of an entry you want to restrict.
For example 'Sources' will restrict both 'main:sources' and 'boot:store/sources'.  

1.This door will first look for a file called "restrict."+username, this way you 
  can have special restrictions for EACH user if you like...

2.If it can not find "restrict."+username it will look for "restrict."+axxlevel,
  for example "restrict.50". This way you can have a restriction for all users 
  with axx level 50.
 
3.If it can't find neither of the above it will look for "restrict", and if this
  is not found there will not apply any restrictions!

Using this smart system you could fexs have a file called "restrict" to restrict
files from all the users, but if you want a special user to have more axx, then 
just make an empty (if you don't want ANY restrictions on him) file called 
"restrict."+his username and he will get other restriction than the others.
The same goes for "restrict."+axxlevel.


@ENDNODE
